ea; Kobori, H., Faculty of Environmental and Information Studies, Tokyo City University, Yokohama 224-0015, Japan; Silander, J.A., Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of Connecticut, Storrs, CT 06269, United States","As a consequence of warming temperatures around the world, spring and autumn phenologies have been shifting, with corresponding changes in the length of the growing season. Our understanding of the spatial and interspecific variation of these changes, however, is limited. Not all species are responding similarly, and there is significant spatial variation in responses even within species. This spatial and interspecific variation complicates efforts to predict phenological responses to ongoing climate change, but must be incorporated in order to build reliable forecasts. Here, we use a long-term dataset (1953-2005) of plant phenological events in spring (flowering and leaf out) and autumn (leaf colouring and leaf fall) throughout Japan and South Korea to build forecasts that account for these sources of variability. Specifically, we used hierarchical models to incorporate the spatial variability in phenological responses to temperature to then forecast species' overall and site-specific responses to global warming. We found that for most species, spring phenology is advancing and autumn phenology is getting later, with the timing of events changing more quickly in autumn compared with the spring. Temporal trends and phenological responses to temperature in East Asia contrasted with results from comparable studies in Europe, where spring events are changing more rapidly than are autumn events. Our results emphasize the need to study multiple species at many sites to understand and forecast regional changes in phenology. © 2010 The Royal Society.","Climate change; East Asia, global warming; Growing season, hierarchical bayes; Plant phenology","ecosystem response; forecasting method; global warming; growing season; hierarchical system; interspecific variation; phenology; plant community; spatial variation; article; biological model; climate change; ecosystem; growth, development and aging; Japan; physiology; plant; plant leaf; regression analysis; season; Climate Change; Ecosystem; Japan; Models, Biological; Plant Leaves; Plants; Regression Analysis; Seasons; Japan; South Korea",,,,,,"Both, C., Bouwhuis, S., Lessells, C.M., Visser, M.E., Climate change and population declines in a long-distance migratory bird (2006) Nature, 441, pp. 81-83. , doi:10. 1038/nature04539; Butler, C.J., The disproportionate effect of global warming on the arrival dates of short-distance migratory birds in North America (2003) Ibis, 145, pp. 484-495. , doi:10. 1046/j.1474-919X.2003.00193.x; Chen, X., East Asia (2003) Phenology: An Integrative Environmental Science, pp. 11-25. , ed. M. D. Schwartz, Dordrecht, The Netherlands: Kluwer; Chuine, I., A unified model for tree phenology (2000) J. Theor. Biol., 207, pp. 337-347. , doi:10.1006/jtbi.2000.2178; Clark, J.S., Why environmental scientists are becoming Bayesians (2005) Ecol. Lett., 8, pp. 2-14. , doi:10.1111/j.1461-0248. 2004.00702.x; Clark, J.S., Mohan, J., Dietze, M., Ibáñez, I., Coexistence: How to identify trophic trade-offs (2003) Ecology, 84, pp. 17-31. , doi:10.1890/0012-9658 2003 0840017: CHTITT2.0.CO;2; Cleland, E.E., Chuine, I., Menzel, A., Mooney, H.A., Schwartz, M.D., Shifting plant phenology in response to global change (2007) Trends Ecol. Evol., 22, p. 357. , doi:10.1016/j.tree.2007.04.003; Cressie, N., Calder, C.A., Clark, J.S., Van Hoef, J.M., Wikle, C.K., Accounting for uncertainty in ecological analysis: The strengths and limitations of hierarchical statistical modeling (2009) Ecol. Appl., 19, pp. 553-570. , doi:10. 1890/07-0744.1; De Beurs, K.M., Henebry, G.M., Land surface phenology, climatic variation, and institutional change: Analyzing agricultural land cover change in Kazakhstan (2003) Remote Sensing Environ., 89, pp. 497-509. , doi:10.1016/j. 